    "body_text": [
        {
            "text": "The novel coronavirus (COVID-19) has rapidly spread across national and international borders, causing severe illness in countries throughout the world and creating a serious public health crisis. 1, 2 The number of ill patients and those suspected to be infected has burdened hospitals and medical equipment supply chains. 3 One way to mitigate some of the logistics problems created by the COVID-19 pandemic is to transition to telehealth services when possible.",
            "cite_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 197,
                    "end": 199,
                    "text": "1,",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF0"
                },
                {
                    "start": 200,
                    "end": 201,
                    "text": "2",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF1"
                },
                {
                    "start": 324,
                    "end": 325,
                    "text": "3",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF2"
                }
            ],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "TO THE EDITOR"
        },
        {
            "text": "Augmenting healthcare systems with telehealth services is feasible, and telemedicine gives practitioners a way to offer medical support to patients during this global pandemic. 3 The US Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, several state public health agencies, many European Union countries, and China have modified existing rules and regulations to permit the increase in utilization of telehealth services and have promoted telehealth as part of the response to the novel coronavirus. [3] [4] [5] [6] Telehealth services can be provided through devices such as computers, smartphones, and tablets. 4 Doctor-patient interaction can still occur despite social distancing and stayat-home orders, 5 and telehealth services eliminate the exposure risk inherent in an in-person clinic visit. Telehealth can be used to monitor patients recovering from COVID-19 after their discharge from the hospital. 7 Telehealth also provides a way to reach populations that have low or no access to care.",
            "cite_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 177,
                    "end": 178,
                    "text": "3",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF2"
                },
                {
                    "start": 494,
